{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d329797b-52af-40ea-a727-4cf584662e6b","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n3. **Via Console.app:**\n   Open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports**\n\nLook for a `.ips` file matching your process name and crash timestamp.\n\n**Tip:** For NativeAOT, you can symbolicate the native frames in the `.ips` file using `atos` or `llvm-symbolizer` with the dSYM bundle (if you built with `-p:StripSymbols=false` or generated dSYMs separately).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"37431805-6d49-4228-b46f-1c1b69650398","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Let me provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":287,"requestId":"2049:2A854:71E363:845AD4:69F01193"},"id":"7e8d9ad6-df30-4a52-a4cb-6cd16014b69e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:47:08.481Z","parentId":"44f0b060-c285-4c99-86ca-8c8ec43415b0"}
